Scope and Purpose
The global financial infrastructure is undergoing a period of profound transformation, characterized by the convergence of physical access points and sophisticated digital ecosystems. For an institution of the scale and complexity of xxplaceholderxx, the security of Self-Service Terminals (SSTs) is not merely a localized operational concern but a critical pillar of the bank’s broader cyber-resilience strategy.1 This technical security standard provides a comprehensive, mandatory framework for the design, implementation, and lifecycle management of all SST assets, including Automated Teller Machines (ATMs), Video Teller Machines (VTMs)—also referred to as Interactive Teller Machines (ITMs)—Cash Deposit Machines (CDMs), and Cash Recycler Machines (CRMs). As these devices evolve into powerful edge computing nodes that handle increasingly complex transaction types, the necessity for a unified, world-class security standard becomes paramount.3
The scope of this standard encompasses the entire functional architecture of the SST environment, reaching beyond the physical chassis to include the internal hardware components, the multi-vendor software stack, network communication protocols, and the backend host integration layers.6 It applies to all SST deployments across the bank's global footprint, ensuring that whether a terminal is situated in a high-traffic metro branch or a remote non-metro location, it adheres to the same rigorous defensive posture.9 Furthermore, this standard governs the security expectations for all internal stakeholders and third-party service providers involved in terminal manufacturing, maintenance, cash-in-transit (CIT) services, and logical monitoring.11
The primary purpose of this documentation is to establish a "Security-by-Design" and "Compliance-by-Design" culture that aligns with the bank’s "shift-left" engineering philosophy.1 By embedding security controls directly into the deployment pipeline and hardware selection criteria, the bank reduces its gross risk and ensures that residual risk remains within the approved appetite.1 This standard is fundamentally designed to harmonize the requirements of global industry frameworks—most notably the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS v4.0.1), PCI PIN Transaction Security (PTS) v7.0, and NIST Special Publication 800-53—with the specific regulatory mandates of jurisdictions like the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) and the Reserve Bank of India (RBI).9

Terminal Type
Abbreviation
Core Functionality and Security Context
Automated Teller Machine
ATM
