8. Micro-segmentation and Network Traffic Encryption
Standard Statement: All SST network traffic must be encapsulated in a secure tunnel (e.g., IPsec VPN or TLS 1.3) and terminated in a secure demilitarized zone (DMZ) or SASE point of presence. Internal network micro-segmentation must be enforced to prevent any direct communication between terminals.
Context and Mechanism: The bank requires the use of host-level next-generation firewalls (NGFW) that provide deep packet inspection (DPI) and protocol filtering for each terminal.28 These firewalls establish a site-to-site IPsec VPN tunnel back to the bank's data center, ensuring that no clear-text transaction data is ever visible on the service provider's network (e.g., 4G/5G/LTE).28 Internally, the network architecture must use micro-segmentation to ensure that an infected terminal cannot scan or attack other terminals in the same subnet.14
Rationale: The terminal’s network connection is its most vulnerable logical point. Without segmentation and encryption, an attacker who gains control of one machine or a network segment could perform a large-scale jackpotting attack across the entire fleet.5
Mapping and Global Standards:
PCI DSS v4.0.1: Requirement 1.2 (Network security controls) and Requirement 4.2 (Protect cardholder data with strong cryptography during transmission).11
NIST SP 800-53 R5: SC-7 (Boundary Protection) and SC-8 (Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity).30
MAS TRM 2021: Mandates for network segmentation and isolation of sensitive systems.14
9. Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for Administrative Access
Standard Statement: All administrative access to SSTs, including local maintenance sessions and remote management via a Terminal Management System (TMS), must require multi-factor authentication (MFA). Static passwords for privileged accounts are strictly prohibited.
Context and Mechanism: The bank mandates the use of MFA solutions that combine "something you have" (e.g., a hardware token or smartphone) with "something you know" or "something you are" (e.g., biometrics).6 For local access, technicians must use a uniquely assigned electronic key or a mobile-generated one-time password (OTP) to open the terminal’s safe or head compartment.6 For remote access, the bank uses a Privileged Access Management (PAM) system that "vaults" credentials and provides MFA-backed session monitoring.6
Rationale: Stolen or compromised administrative credentials are a leading cause of jackpotting and data breach incidents.21 MFA ensures that even if an attacker obtains a password, they cannot gain control of the machine without a second factor.37
Mapping and Global Standards:
PCI DSS v4.0.1: Requirement 8.4.2 (MFA for all access to the cardholder data environment).11
NIST SP 800-53 R5: IA-2 (Identification and Authentication - Organizational Users) and AC-2 (Account Management).30
ISO 27001:2022: Control A 5.15 (Access Control) and A 5.18 (Access Rights).37
10. Point-of-Interaction (POI) Integrity and SRED
Standard Statement: All payment terminals within the SST must be PCI PTS-approved and have Secure Reading and Exchange of Data (SRED) enabled. This ensures that card data is encrypted immediately upon capture at the read head.
Context and Mechanism: SRED-enabled readers protect account data from "memory scraping" malware that attempts to steal clear-text data while it is in the terminal’s RAM.11 When part of a PCI-listed Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) solution, the terminal hardware manages the encryption process autonomously, ensuring that no clear-text data is ever exposed to the terminal’s operating system or the bank’s internal network.11
Rationale: Protecting data at the moment of capture is the most effective way to minimize the scope of a data breach. By using SRED, the bank ensures that even a total compromise of the OS does not provide the attacker with usable cardholder data.11
Mapping and Global Standards:
PCI PTS v7.0: Security requirements for PIN entry devices and card readers.16
PCI P2PE Standard: Requirements for secure encryption solutions.11
NIST SP 800-53 R5: SC-13 (Cryptographic Protection).
11. Centralized Real-Time Monitoring and Log Intelligence
Standard Statement: All SST units must transmit security-relevant logs in real-time to the bank’s centralized SIEM platform. The logging configuration must cover physical sensor events, system integrity alerts, and transactional anomalies.
Context and Mechanism: xxplaceholderxx utilizes a Databricks-based "Lakehouse" architecture to aggregate and analyze billions of security events from its global estate.34 SSTs must log events such as safe door openings, unexpected reboots, communication outages, and any blocked execution attempts by the whitelisting client.6 Machine learning models are applied to this data to identify patterns indicative of "cash-out" attacks or hardware tampering in progress.28
Rationale: Rapid detection is essential for mitigating the impact of an attack. Without centralized, real-time logging, a terminal could be compromised and "emptied" of cash before the bank’s security operations center (SOC) is even aware of the incident.6
Mapping and Global Standards:
PCI DSS v4.0.1: Requirement 10.4.1 (Automated log reviews and real-time alerts).15
NIST SP 800-53 R5: AU-2 (Event Logging) and AU-6 (Audit Review, Analysis, and Reporting).13
MAS TRM 2021: Requirements for centralized log management and SIEM integration.14

